comment.en:
The "Bildungsgangniveau" is a "Niveau" that describes the requirements within an "Bildungsgang" and characterizes the differences in performance levels between various educational tracks.
It describes the depth and level of demand with which learning content and competencies are addressed within this educational track.
In the ontology, a distinction is made between "Hauptschulniveau", "Realschulniveau", "Gymnasialniveau Sek I", and "Gymnasialniveau Sek II".
These correspond to the basic, intermediate, and advanced requirements used in some lower secondary curricula to categorize competences.
While the "Fachniveau" describes the specific requirements in a single subject within the upper secondary level of the Gymnasium track, the "Bildungsgangniveau" refers to the level of an entire educational track aimed at a specific qualification.

comment.en:
The "Fachniveau" is a "Niveau". It refers to the level of requirements for a specific subject in upper secondary education ("Sekundarstufe II") and indicates whether a "Curriculares Element" is assigned to a "Grundkurs" or a "Leistungskurs".
The two ‚ÄúFachniveaus‚Äù differ in the complexity and depth of instruction, as well as in the scope of content and the performance expectations.
While the "Bildungsgangniveau" describes the level of an entire educational track aimed at a specific qualification, the "Fachniveau" refers to the specific requirements of a subject within the Gymnasium track of upper secondary education.

CE-Kompetenzspezifikation: Die Sch√ºlerinnen und Sch√ºler setzen sich auf der Grundlage ihrer Kenntnisse bewusst mit der englischen Sprache und den mit ihr verbundenen Kulturr√§umen auseinander.

comment.en:
A ‚ÄúCE-Kompetenzspezifikation‚Äù is a ‚ÄúCurriculares Element‚Äù that describes a competence.
It usually contains an operator and begins with ‚ÄúThe students [...]‚Äù or ‚ÄúThe learners [...]‚Äù for example.
The ontology distinguishes between ‚ÄúCE-Kompetenzspezifikation‚Äù and ‚ÄúKompetenz‚Äù:
A competence is understood as the ability of a learner to apply knowledge and skills to solve problems (cf. KMK). 
In contrast to competence, which is anchored in the learner as an ability or skill, the ‚ÄúCE-Kompetenzspezifikation‚Äù is the description of this competence within the framework of a curriculum or educational standard.

comment.de:
Die ‚ÄúSchulstufe‚Äù ist eine ‚ÄúInformationseinheit‚Äù.
Sie bezeichnet eine bestimmte Phase der schulischen Laufbahn, in der Lernende bestimmte Ziele gem√§√ü den Anforderungen des Bildungssystems erreichen sollen. 
Schulstufen dienen dazu, den Lernenden einen strukturierten Lernweg zu bieten, in dem die p√§dagogischen und didaktischen Anforderungen an die jeweiligen Altersgruppen angepasst sind.
Die Schulstufe umfasst je nach Bildungsgang bzw. Bundesland festgelegte Jahrgangsstufen.
Sie unterscheidet sich von:  
dem ‚ÄúBildungsgang‚Äù (der sich auf die Art des Abschlusses bezieht, z. B. Gymnasialer Bildungsgang oder Realschulbildungsgang), 
dem "Bildungsgangniveau" (welches das Niveau eines Bildungsgangs beschreibt) und 
dem ‚ÄúFachniveau‚Äù (das die Tiefe und den Umfang eines spezifischen Fachs der Sekundarstufe II beschreibt).
Im Bereich der allgemeinbildenden Schulen wird unterschieden zwischen der ‚ÄúPrimarstufe‚Äù (auch Grundschule genannt), der ‚ÄúSekundarstufe I‚Äù und der ‚ÄúSekundarstufe II‚Äù (auch gymnasiale Oberstufe genannt).
comment.en:
The "Schulstufe" is an ‚Äúinformation content entity‚Äù.
It refers to a specific phase of the school career in which learners are expected to achieve certain goals according to the requirements of the education system.
"Schulstufen" provide learners with a structured learning path, with pedagogical and didactic requirements adapted to the respective age groups.
Each "Schulstufe" includes designated grade levels depending on the educational track and federal state.
It differs from:
the "Bildungsgang" (which refers to the type of qualification, e.g., "Gymnasialer Bildungsgang" or "Realschulbildungsgang"),
the "Bildungsgangniveau" (which describes the level of an educational track), and
the "Fachniveau" (which describes the depth and scope of a specific subject in upper secondary education).
In general education, we distinguish between the "Primarstufe" (also called Grundschule), the "Sekundarstufe I", and the "Sekundarstufe II" (also known as the upper secondary level or "gymnasiale Oberstufe").

The "Primarbereich", "Sekundarbereich I", and "Sekundarbereich II" are instances of the class "Schulstufe".

Ein ‚ÄúCurriculares Element‚Äù ist eine Informationseinheit, die bei der Beschreibung der Bestandteile eines Lehrplans oder Bildungsstandards verwendet wird.

In der Ontologie fungiert das ‚ÄúCurriculare Element" als Superklasse, um die Elemente zu ordnen, aus denen sich Beschreibungen der zu erwerbenden Inhalte und Kompetenzen eines Lehrplans oder eines Bildungsstandards zusammensetzen.

comment.en:
A ‚ÄúCurriculares Element‚Äù is an information content entity used to describe the components of a curriculum or educational standard.

In the ontology, the "Curriculares Element" serves as a superordinate category to structure the components that describe the content and competencies to be acquired within a curriculum or educational standard.

A ‚ÄúCurriculares Element‚Äù can also have a function that defines its purpose within the curriculum in more detail. This allows the state-specific components of the curricula to be mapped, as common functions can be assigned to them.

Subclasses of the ‚ÄúCurriculares Element‚Äù that are not state-specific are labelled with the prefix ‚ÄòCE-‚Äô.

Ein Lehrplan ist eine Informationseinheit, die eine systematische Zusammenstellung von curricularen Elementen umfasst. Er definiert verbindlich die Kompetenzen und Inhalte, die Sch√ºlerinnen und Sch√ºler in einem bestimmten Fach, einer Jahrgangsstufe, einer Schulart oder einem Bildungsgang eines Bundeslandes erwerben sollen.

Ein Lehrplan ist immer spezifisch auf die Bildungspolitik eines Bundeslandes bezogen und unterscheidet sich von bundesland√ºbergreifenden Bildungsstandards, die von der Kultusministerkonferenz (KMK) verabschiedet werden und als Grundlage f√ºr die Entwicklung konkreter Lehrpl√§ne in den L√§ndern dienen k√∂nnen.

comment.en:
A curriculum is an information content entity that comprises a systematic compilation of curricular elements. It bindingly defines the skills and learning content that students should acquire in a particular subject, grade, type of school or educational level in a federal state.

A curriculum is always specific to the educational policy of a federal state and differs from the nationwide educational standards that are published by the Kultusministerkonferenz (KMK). They can serve as the basis for the development of specific curricula in the federal states.

In addition to the binding requirements, the curriculum often also contains information on the didactic and methodological design of lessons as well as cross-references to related and interdisciplinary skills and content from other school subjects. Depending on the federal state, curricula can have different names.

comment.en:
The "Gymnasiale Bildungsgang" is a "Bildungsgang".
It aims to prepare learners for the "Abitur" and subsequent university studies.
Typically, this educational track extends to grade 12 or 13 and concludes with the "Allgemeine Hochschulreife" (Abitur), which grants access to universities and higher education institutions.
The curriculum content for the "Gymnasiale Bildungsgang" is more academically demanding and theoretical than that of the "Hauptschul-" or "Realschulbildungsgang".
The "Gymnasiale Bildungsgang" does not necessarily have to be completed at a Gymnasium; it can also be pursued at ‚ÄúGesamt- oder Gemeinschaftsschulen‚Äù offering schooling at the Gymnasium level with the goal of achieving the "Allgemeine Hochschulreife".

IAO_0000116.value:
Parthood requires the part and the whole to have compatible classes: only an occurrent have an occurrent as part; only a process can have a process as part; only a continuant can have a continuant as part; only an independent continuant can have an independent continuant as part; only a specifically dependent continuant can have a specifically dependent continuant as part; only a generically dependent continuant can have a generically dependent continuant as part. (This list is not exhaustive.)

A continuant cannot have an occurrent as part: use 'participates in'. An occurrent cannot have a continuant as part: use 'has participant'. An immaterial entity cannot have a material entity as part: use 'location of'. An independent continuant cannot have a specifically dependent continuant as part: use 'bearer of'. A specifically dependent continuant cannot have an independent continuant as part: use 'inheres in'.
Everything has itself as a part. Any part of any part of a thing is itself part of that thing. Two distinct things cannot have each other as a part.

Occurrents are not subject to change and so parthood between occurrents holds for all the times that the part exists. Many continuants are subject to change, so parthood between continuants will only hold at certain times, but this is difficult to specify in OWL. See http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ro/docs/temporal-semantics/

The quality (a specifically dependent continuant) concretizes the journal article (a generically dependent continuant), and both depend on that copy of the printed journal (an independent continuant).

IAO_0000115.value: A relationship between a specifically dependent continuant or process and a generically dependent continuant, in which the generically dependent continuant depends on some independent continuant in virtue of the fact that the specifically dependent continuant or process also depends on that same independent continuant. Multiple specifically dependent continuants or processes can concretize the same generically dependent continuant.
